Part one (cleaning)

Answer each of the following questions using R code to get an answer. Write a separate code chunk for each variable, once all the data manipulation is done, show the values in a barchart or histogram and comment on the plot.

  1. Data cleaning: the values IAP, DK and NA all encode missing values. Replace all of these instances by the value NA. 
happy[happy == "IAP"] <- NA
happy[happy == "DK"] <- NA
happy[happy == "NA"] <- NA
#another way to do it -> happy = replace(happy, happy == "IAP", NA) {do for each one}

happy$AGE = as.numeric(happy$AGE)
  1. Bring all levels of factors into a sensible order. For marital you could e.g.order the levels according to average age. 
happy$HAPPY = as.factor(happy$HAPPY) 
happy$MARITAL = as.factor(happy$MARITAL)
happy$HEALTH = as.factor(happy$HEALTH)
happy$DEGREE = as.factor(happy$DEGREE)
happy$SEX = as.factor(happy$SEX)
happy$FINRELA = as.factor(happy$FINRELA)
happy$PARTYID = as.factor(happy$PARTYID)

happy = happy %>% mutate(DEGREE = factor(DEGREE, levels = c("LT HIGH SCHOOL","HIGH SCHOOL", "JUNIOR COLLEGE", "GRADUATE", 
                                                            "BACHELOR"))) %>% 
  mutate(FINRELA = factor(FINRELA, levels = c("FAR BELOW AVERAGE", "BELOW AVERAGE", "AVERAGE", "ABOVE AVERAGE", 
                                              "FAR ABOVE AVERAGE"))) %>%
  mutate(HEALTH= factor(HEALTH, levels = c("POOR", "FAIR", "EXCELLENT", "GOOD")))

  1. How do average happiness levels change over age? 
happy.age = happy %>%
  group_by(age) %>% 
  summarise(m.age = mean(as.numeric(happy), na.rm  = TRUE))

happy.age %>% ggplot(aes(x = age, y = m.age)) + geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

  1. Are Republicans or Democrats happier? Compare average happiness levels over partyid.
happy.party = happy %>%
  group_by(partyid) %>%
  summarise(m.partyid = mean(as.numeric(happy), na.rm  = TRUE))

happy.party %>%  ggplot(aes(x = partyid)) + geom_bar(aes(weight = m.partyid))

  1. How are financial relations associated with average happiness levels? Is this association different for men and women? 
happy.finrela = happy %>%
  group_by(finrela, sex) %>%
  summarise(m.finrela = mean(as.numeric(happy), na.rm  = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'finrela'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
happy.finrela %>%  ggplot(aes(x = finrela, fill = sex)) + geom_bar(aes(weight = m.finrela), position = position_dodge2())

Health and Sex Answer: The people with the excellent health are the happiest. As well as the males are a little more happy than females in the excellent and good categories. The better the health the more happy people are. 

happy.health.age = happy %>%
  group_by(health, sex) %>%
  summarise(m.happy = mean(as.numeric(happy), na.rm  = TRUE)) %>%
  arrange(m.happy)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'health'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
happy.health.age %>%  ggplot(aes(x = health, fill = sex)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(weight = m.happy), position = position_dodge2()) +
  labs(title = "", y = "Happiness", x = "Health")

Michael Moore

partyid and degree Answer: Based on the bar chart below, we can make a couple of assumptions based on the data. Firstly we can see that partyid is a strong indicator of happiness. We can see that the strong republicans are the happiest and that the farther left your partyid is the less happy your are. However we can see a unique trend in the data: near dems are the least happy. On top of this if you go left more after near dem it indicates you will be happier. On top of this distinctive trend we can see the an individuals happiness is also strongly indicated by their education. People with graduate level education are happier on average than people with less education. Overall, There is a lot of interesting information we can glean from the chart.

happy.degree.age = happy %>%
  group_by(partyid, degree) %>%
  summarise(m.happy = mean(as.numeric(happy), na.rm  = TRUE)) %>%
  arrange(m.happy)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'partyid'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
happy.degree.age %>%  ggplot(aes(x = partyid, fill = degree)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(weight = m.happy), position = position_dodge2()) +
  labs(title = "", y = "Happiness", x = "Degree") +
  coord_flip()
